. What is Cross-Zone Load Balancing?

A feature of AWS Elastic Load Balancing (ELB)

Distributes incoming traffic evenly across targets in all enabled Availability Zones

Prevents one AZ from becoming a bottleneck

Improves availability, fault tolerance, and performance

2. How Cross-Zone Load Balancing Works

ELB has load balancer nodes in each AZ

With cross-zone enabled:

Each load balancer node can send traffic to targets in all AZs

If one AZ becomes unavailable:

Traffic is automatically routed to healthy instances in other AZs

üìå Exam Concept:
Traffic distribution is balanced across all instances, not just within the same AZ.

3. Without vs With Cross-Zone Load Balancing
Without Cross-Zone

Each AZ handles traffic only for instances in that AZ

Uneven traffic if AZs have different number of instances

With Cross-Zone

Traffic is distributed evenly across all instances in all AZs

Better utilization of instances

4. Benefits of Cross-Zone Load Balancing
‚úÖ Improved Availability

Protects against AZ failure

No single AZ overload

‚úÖ Improved Performance

Even traffic distribution

Reduced latency & better response times

‚úÖ Better Resource Utilization

All EC2 instances receive traffic evenly

Avoids idle instances in low-traffic AZs

5. Limitations / Considerations
‚ö†Ô∏è Increased Cost

You must run:

Load balancer nodes

EC2 instances

In multiple AZs

Cross-AZ data transfer may add cost (exam-relevant nuance)

‚ö†Ô∏è Architecture Complexity

Requires:

Multi-AZ design

Proper health checks

Correct subnet setup

6. Cross-Zone Load Balancing & ELB Types (EXAM FAVORITE)
Load Balancer	Cross-Zone Default
ALB	‚úî Enabled by default
NLB	‚ùå Disabled by default (can be enabled)
CLB	‚ùå Disabled by default
GWLB	‚úî Enabled by default

üìå Exam Tip:
üëâ ALB = cross-zone ON by default

7. One-Line Exam Summary

Cross-Zone Load Balancing evenly distributes traffic across all targets in all Availability Zones, improving availability and performance.

‚úÖ PREDICTED MCQs (SAA-C03 ‚Äì HIGH PROBABILITY)
MCQ 1

What is the main purpose of cross-zone load balancing?

A. Reduce latency within a subnet
B. Distribute traffic evenly across AZs
C. Encrypt traffic between ELB and targets
D. Reduce number of EC2 instances

‚úÖ Answer: B

MCQ 2

With cross-zone load balancing enabled, traffic is distributed:

A. Only within the same AZ
B. Only to the closest instance
C. Evenly across all instances in all AZs
D. Only to instances in public subnets

‚úÖ Answer: C

MCQ 3

Which load balancer has cross-zone load balancing enabled by default?

A. Classic Load Balancer
B. Network Load Balancer
C. Application Load Balancer
D. None of the above

‚úÖ Answer: C

MCQ 4

What happens if one Availability Zone becomes unavailable?

A. ELB stops routing traffic
B. Application becomes unavailable
C. Traffic is routed to other AZs
D. Load balancer fails

‚úÖ Answer: C

MCQ 5

Which is a potential drawback of cross-zone load balancing?

A. Lower performance
B. Higher latency
C. Increased cost
D. Reduced scalability

‚úÖ Answer: C

MCQ 6

Without cross-zone load balancing, traffic is distributed:

A. Evenly across all AZs
B. Only within the originating AZ
C. Randomly
D. Only to healthy instances in another region

‚úÖ Answer: B

MCQ 7

Cross-zone load balancing primarily improves which AWS design principle?

A. Cost optimization
B. Security
C. High availability
D. Operational excellence

‚úÖ Answer: C

MCQ 8

Which load balancer requires you to manually enable cross-zone load balancing?

A. ALB
B. GWLB
C. NLB
D. Route 53

‚úÖ Answer: C

MCQ 9

Cross-zone load balancing helps prevent which issue?

A. Data loss
B. AZ bottleneck
C. IAM misconfiguration
D. Security group failure

‚úÖ Answer: B

MCQ 10

Which scenario MOST benefits from cross-zone load balancing?

A. Single-AZ deployment
B. Stateless multi-AZ web application
C. Offline batch processing
D. Backup storage

‚úÖ Answer: B
